<p>
  pet insurance is the uk's quietest loyalty penalty offender. unlike car insurance — where comparison sites and fca rules provide some transparency — pet insurance sits in a regulatory grey area where renewal hikes are severe, poorly disclosed, and almost never challenged.
</p>

<h3>how bad is it</h3>

<p>
  analysis of 2025 pet insurance renewal data shows average premium increases of 18–34% at renewal. for older pets — dogs over 7, cats over 10 — renewal hikes regularly exceed 40%. owners of older pets are often trapped: pre-existing conditions make switching to a new insurer impossible, so they have to accept whatever price their existing insurer offers.
</p>

<p>
  a 9-year-old labrador with arthritis: year 1 premium £480, year 2 £620 (+29%), year 3 £840 (+35%), year 4 £1,100 (+31%). over 4 years, the loyalty penalty adds £620 to the total cost. and because of the pre-existing condition exclusion, the owner has no alternative.
</p>

<h3>what to do about it</h3>

<p>
  for young, healthy pets: switch every year. the new customer rate is almost always lower than the renewal rate. for older pets with conditions: negotiate. call your insurer, mention the price increase, ask if they can match a competitor quote for a new policy. sometimes they'll reduce the increase — not always, but it costs nothing to ask.
</p>

<p>
  also consider: lifetime policies vs annual policies. a lifetime policy covers conditions year after year but costs more upfront. an annual policy is cheaper but resets coverage each year — meaning ongoing conditions are excluded on renewal. the savings from an annual policy evaporate the moment your pet develops a chronic condition.
</p>
